I guess, well, I didn't...

36:46.302 --> 36:49.107
You were 54, I guess, when you published it?

36:49.127 --> 36:52.774
In 1967, published me in 55.

36:54.137 --> 36:55.820
Got arrived in 53.

36:55.880 --> 37:02.332
Now, I did a book in 1957 for young people, for jazz, called Giants of Jazz.

37:02.893 --> 37:06.640
But this series, called Oral History, is

37:06.923 --> 37:08.224
began when I was 55.

37:08.244 --> 37:11.467
How did you happen onto this concept of oral history?

37:11.487 --> 37:15.590
Well, you're sitting right now in the home of Andre Schifrin, who was my publisher.

37:15.691 --> 37:16.071
Famous?

37:16.992 --> 37:18.893
And Andre's the guy responsible.

37:18.913 --> 37:19.234
Really?

37:19.254 --> 37:26.160
He saw something I'd written, or an interview was republished on the radio station, and he got this idea.

37:26.180 --> 37:34.166
And he had published, before I met him, he had published an American edition of a book by Jan Myrdal.

37:34.247 --> 37:35.968
He's the son of Donald Myrdal.

37:36.286 --> 37:42.213
wrote The American Dilemma, and his mother won the Nobel Peace Prize at group Alvomir.

37:42.233 --> 38:02.136
This is Yan, who visited China shortly after the revolution, and he visited the small town in China, North China, and he's describing changes that took place in the lives, daily lives of these people as a result before and after the revolution.

38:02.156 --> 38:06.040
So Andre Shepard called me shortly thereafter, publishing this book,

38:06.509 --> 38:09.092
report from a Chinese village.

38:09.732 --> 38:12.415
He said, how about you reporting for an American village?

38:12.855 --> 38:13.856
He said, Chicago.

38:14.837 --> 38:31.995
And I said, you out of your mind, how can you compare a city, a huge industrial complex Chicago to a small Chinese village in Chicago where a million things are happening, the civil rights, it was the 60s, the civil rights revolution, the cybernetic revolution, autumn, how can you do that?

38:32.275 --> 38:34.457
But I did it, Division Street America.

38:34.775 --> 38:36.497
And it was rather well received.

38:37.078 --> 38:42.686
So six months later, Andre says again on the phone, how about a book about the Great American Depression?

38:43.868 --> 38:45.710
So I say, are you out of your mind?

38:46.732 --> 38:48.054
And I do the hard times.

38:48.594 --> 38:50.056
And that's well received.

38:50.137 --> 38:52.620
Did you have this phrase, this oral history?

38:53.221 --> 38:56.385
Well, oral history is an old, old phrase, you know.

38:56.405 --> 38:58.769
Yeah, but really where it's the voice of the individual.

38:58.929 --> 38:59.770
Yeah.

39:00.222 --> 39:05.047
The authorial intrusion is... But oral history... If it's there, it's not there.

39:05.387 --> 39:08.570
Oral history has preceded the written word.

39:08.750 --> 39:11.232
You know, before the printing press, there was oral history.

39:11.553 --> 39:12.794
People are storytellers.

39:12.834 --> 39:14.936
Those people Alex Haley talked about.

39:15.376 --> 39:19.200
The Griots were there long before Gutenberg invented the printing press.

39:19.220 --> 39:23.203
And in America, Appalachian country, are still storytellers.

39:23.804 --> 39:28.148
So, in fact, I'm not really a historian, a scholar.

39:28.168 --> 39:29.149
I'm not a scholar.

39:29.517 --> 39:34.221
So I call myself a maybe oral journalism or a guerrilla journalist.

39:34.582 --> 39:38.805
And I think earlier you asked how I work, and I say improvise around.

39:39.426 --> 39:43.770
Well, a journalist does work with the immediate, I guess, and the historian evaluates.

39:44.270 --> 39:48.854
So what would you feel that you're providing the raw material then for future historians?

39:48.874 --> 39:49.595
Yeah, in a sense.

39:49.635 --> 39:53.038
Someone did say that about the books.

39:53.058 --> 39:58.663
But the idea of people telling about their lives

39:59.268 --> 40:02.511
It was also done way before me during the New Deal.

40:03.352 --> 40:05.955
I mentioned the WPA, the Work Project Administration.

40:05.975 --> 40:08.037
They had a writer's project.

40:08.478 --> 40:11.421
They had a theater project.

40:11.441 --> 40:16.967
And then the writer's project, different writers in different states were seeing old people.

40:17.988 --> 40:26.237
In fact, them old black people were slaves, and this was in the 30s, were still slaves in their childhood, remembering the early days.

40:26.555 --> 40:32.063
And there was railroad folklore and all sorts of American folklore that was gathered.

40:32.083 --> 40:38.471
That was also oral history, in a way, that the people on this New Deal project were doing.

40:38.491 --> 40:44.319
Now, when you sat down with your subjects here, did you have a script?

40:44.500 --> 40:46.923
Did you have an agenda to pursue?

40:46.943 --> 40:47.123
No.

40:47.143 --> 40:49.487
Or did you pretty much... No.

40:49.507 --> 40:51.229
It's the nature of conversation.

40:51.935 --> 40:55.780
I had an idea about what's going to be about working, about the job.

40:56.140 --> 40:57.482
What's it like to be a welder?

40:57.542 --> 40:58.463
Tell me about your day.

40:58.483 --> 41:00.446
But I mean this particular book here.

41:00.466 --> 41:01.247
Oh, no, no.

41:01.688 --> 41:05.613
No, it's just certain old people I wanted, certain contemporaries.

41:05.633 --> 41:07.255
I wanted to see David Brower.

41:07.755 --> 41:11.460
He thought of the enfant terrible, the environmental movement.

41:11.480 --> 41:18.349
David Brower would find earth, you know, friends, earth, or he found a group to fight the polluters.

41:18.769 --> 41:21.553
But then if the group got a little soft, he'd leave it and

41:21.803 --> 41:24.246
found another group, more militant.

41:24.686 --> 41:28.170
And each time he would do this, it makes it easier for the ones who follow me.

41:28.290 --> 41:31.113
They seem so reasonable in contrast to me.

41:31.133 --> 41:32.875
I want to make them seem reasonable.

41:33.336 --> 41:35.979
Well, David Brower, I ought to get him in the book.

41:35.999 --> 41:40.504
And he said, he more or less, he's in the prologue, and he more or less sets the theme.

41:40.524 --> 41:46.070
He says, you know, this century is the wildest, craziest century he's ever been.

41:46.110 --> 41:50.595
The Great Depression, World War II that changed the world,

41:50.997 --> 41:58.264
The Cold War that killed conversation and still to some extent has treated trivia instead of conversation.

41:58.825 --> 42:03.389
The Vietnam War, the computers, all this in this one central.

42:03.409 --> 42:04.330
The Holocaust.

42:05.291 --> 42:08.054
And the Holocaust, of course, and Hiroshima.

42:08.094 --> 42:08.474
Unprecedented.

42:08.494 --> 42:10.436
Auschwitz and Hiroshima.

42:10.496 --> 42:19.165
Think about a man who has created Hamlet and Don Giovanni and Beethoven did the Ninth

42:19.735 --> 42:33.009
as also the same species has done Hiroshima and Nagasaki and Auschwitz, the same generation almost.

42:33.029 --> 42:42.218
